  "prompt": "How does student loan forgiveness work?",
  "response": "Student loan forgiveness is a process that can eliminate some or all of a borrower's federal student loan debt under certain conditions:\n\n1. Public Service Loan Forgiveness (PSLF)\n- For borrowers working full-time in government or non-profit sectors\n- Requires 120 qualifying monthly payments\n- Remaining loan balance is forgiven after 10 years of service\n\n2. Teacher Loan Forgiveness\n- For teachers working in low-income schools\n- Up to $17,500 in loan forgiveness after 5 consecutive years of teaching\n\n3. Income-Driven Repayment Plans\n- Payments are based on income and family size\n- Remaining balance may be forgiven after 20-25 years of payments\n\n4. Biden Administration's Loan Forgiveness Plan\n- Initially proposed $10,000 forgiveness for most borrowers\n- $20,000 for Pell Grant recipients\n- Currently on hold due to legal challenges\n\n5. Disability Discharge\n- Total and permanent disability can qualify for loan discharge\n- Requires documentation of disability status\n\n6. Closed School Discharge\n- Loans can be forgiven if school closes while student is enrolled\n\nNote: Requirements and eligibility vary, and most programs apply only to federal student loans.",
